Introduction

For my report, I decided to focus on the frequency that I receive emails in, how many emails I exchange in each month and what days and how long are the emails I usually send are compared to the ones I received.

I applied the grammar of graphics:

  1. A simple bar chart to show the number of emails I exchange every month, classified by whether it was sent or received to gain idea of the proportions. I used bar charts since they are extremely useful for demonstrating proportions. geom_bar() from ggplot()

  2. To show the number of emails each month, I did four separate line charts with the x-axis being the days of the week, to show the trends of how the number of emails increase or decrease depending on the day itself. I used line charts as they are useful to show how a variable changes over a given time period. This was done using geom_line() from ggplot().

  3. A scatter plot where I grouped emails by whether I sent them or received them. Then I found out how they stand according to the length of the email subject and color coded it with the day email was sent. I used a scatter plot as it is helpful to visualize every single entity (email) and how it stands by itself compared to other emails geom_jitter() from ggplot()

  4. I produced an animation of the line chart to help visualize the variance between the patterns of the number of emails exchanged in every month and how it varies according to the days of each month. Animation will provide gradual presentation of information, which will help convey it more clearly and easily.

tried but didnt work I tried to make a box plot for the mean of the length of the emails I receive considering my results. However it didnt communicate what I wanted it to in the efficient way that it should. It just produced a line, without any additional information. Thus, making it an ineffective visualization. This I found out was due to my sample size being really small, thus unable to create an efficient box plot.

Visualisations

The visualization below is a bar chart, It shows the number of emails I exchanged in each month. In addition, it shows the proportion of emails I receive vs emails I send. This visualization helped understand how many emails I exchange. It also helped me understand that I have an extremely higher proportion of emails received than emails sent.

This visualization has told me that March, especially Thursday, has the highest number of emails sent. In addition, March had the most significant changes in the number of emails sends while April had more fluctuations (i.e increases and decreases). I learnt that February and May have the least numbers of emails exchanged. I also learnt that generally, more emails are exchanged at the start of the week, i.e Monday to Thursday.

From this graph, due to the color filter, it is apparent that Wednesday is the day where I receive more emails while Thursday is that day I send more emails. Generally, I send significantly fewer emails than what I receive. In addition, I generally tend to have less words in the emails I send than the ones I receive as the graph for sent emails is more inclined to the left than the one with received emails.

I decided to further enhance the presentation of the information by providing the number of emails sent for each month gradually. As seen below user can compare the difference between the number of emails sent for each month by the days it was sent to the month before it.

Learning reflections

One important idea I learnt in Module 4: Creating static and dynamic visualizations is how to be able to animate a visualization to further communicate and demonstrate your findings.

My project demonstrates creativity through the data manipulations that I made. As in my code, I had to create separate tables and join them together using full_join(). I also had to turn each day of the week into a number to produce a line chart. This was done by creating a list of weekday using contain c(). I also had to find what number corresponds to which day of the week match() functions. This was all done to create a linear representation. I also chose accurate visualization to communicate my findings. This was not gone through in the lectures and I was set on my own way to learn how to deliver the result I had in mind.

I am curious to learn more about animations and what kind of different animation functions I can use to produce different graphs.

library(gganimate)
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(transformr)
library(magick)

email_data <- read_csv("https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/e/2PACX-1vTiBYmV6g4HkFu9Cnjyc15j4HhMaF8_l1wlJ0QiYZlp7oHWqd1uhCCNtLjFCSA1lWsRRYGrxiEz27TJ/pub?gid=0&single=true&output=csv") %>%
  mutate(email_type = ifelse(email_from == "Seifeldin Farah <sfar671@aucklanduni.ac.nz>", "sent", "received")) %>%
  glimpse()


## To help give each day a numerical value by assigning it to an index 
day_names <- c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday")


# FINDING NUMBER OF EMAILS I RECIEVED ON A MONTHLY BASIS 
emails_recieved_monthly <- email_data %>%
  filter(email_to == "sfar671@aucklanduni.ac.nz") %>%
  group_by(email_month) %>%
  summarise(num_emails_recieved = n()) 

## FINDING EMAILS I SEND MONTHLY 
emails_sent_monthly <- email_data %>%
  filter(email_from == "Seifeldin Farah <sfar671@aucklanduni.ac.nz>") %>%
  group_by(email_month) %>%
  summarise(num_emails_sent= n())

## joining both
emails_monthly <- emails_recieved_monthly %>%
  full_join(emails_sent_monthly, by = "email_month") %>%
  mutate(num_emails_received = coalesce(num_emails_recieved, 0),
         num_emails_sent = coalesce(num_emails_sent, 0))

# FINDING ON WHAT DAY USUALLY RESULTS COME OUT THROUGH EMAIL
emails_for_results_by_day <- email_data %>%
  filter(str_detect(tolower(email_subject), "result")) %>%
  group_by(email_day) %>%
  summarise(num_emails_per_day_of_week = n())

# FINDING OUT WHO I GET EMAILED BY THE MOST 
emailed_by <- email_data %>%
  group_by(email_from) %>%
  summarise(total_emails = n()) %>%
  print()

## Mean number of emails exchanged every month 
mean_length_emails_of_each_month <- email_data %>%
  group_by(email_month) %>%
  summarise(mean_email_length_exchange=mean(length(email_subject)))

## emails grouped by days 
emails_by_day <- email_data %>%
  mutate(email_day_number = match(email_day, day_names)) %>% #matched each day to a number to help me produce a line chart
  group_by(email_month,email_day_number) %>%
  summarise(num_emails = n())

# graph one is a  bar graph of the number of emails i exchange every month
graph_one <- ggplot(emails_monthly, aes(x = email_month)) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = num_emails_received, fill = "Received"), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  geom_bar(aes(y = num_emails_sent, fill = "Sent"), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Number of Emails Sent and Received Each Month", x = "Month", y = "Number of Emails") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Received" = "#7140F5", "Sent" = "#FF5733"), name = "Type of Email") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

## graph two is to make box plot for mean of emails containing results (DIDN'T WORK)
graph_two <- ggplot() +
  geom_boxplot(data=emails_for_results_by_day,  aes(x=num_emails_per_day_of_week, y = email_day)) +
  geom_point(data=emails_for_results_by_day,  aes(x=num_emails_per_day_of_week, y = email_day))


## graph three is line plot to show emails by month 
graph_three <- ggplot(data = emails_by_day, aes(x = email_day_number, y = num_emails)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = email_month, group = email_month)) + #grouped it by email_month and did a different color for each month 
  facet_wrap(~ email_month, nrow = 3) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:7, labels = day_names) + ## here i defined that the axis will go from 1 to 7, and did day names as label to show the name of the day instead of a number to make the visual representation more meaningful
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=45)) # i angled the x axis labels for readability

## graph four 
graph_four <- email_data %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_jitter(aes(x=length(email_subject), y = email_type, color = email_day)) +
  labs(title="Length of email subjects, classified by whether it was sent or received", x="Length of email", y="Email Type")

## animation 
animation <- ggplot(data = emails_by_day, aes(x = email_day_number, y = num_emails)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = email_month, group = email_month)) +
  facet_wrap(~ email_month, nrow = 3) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:7, labels = day_names) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45)) +
  transition_states(email_month)

ggsave("bargraph.png", graph_one)
ggsave("emailsday.png", graph_three)
ggsave("scatter.png", graph_four)
anim_save("animation.gif", animation)
print(graph_two)
